article.description: Brad Banks threw for three touchdowns and ran for two more as No. 6 Iowa won its eighth straight game by defeating Northwestern 62-10 Saturday.
article.headline: Banks makes final home game memorable

images.name: Banks_Brad 021109 inline
images.caption: Iowa quarterback Brad Banks threw three TD passes and ran for two more.

article.linkText: Banks pays off with 5 TDs in Iowa rout of Northwestern
article.story:
IOWA CITY, Iowa (AP) -- Brad Banks is the main reason Iowa is
hanging around the cluttered race for those coveted BCS spots.

<photo1>

	   He threw for three touchdowns and ran for two more, leading the
sixth-ranked Hawkeyes to their eighth straight victory Saturday,
62-10 over Northwestern.

	   Banks made the most of his chances during his final home game
for the Hawkeyes (10-1, 7-0). The nation's leader in pass
efficiency completed all 10 of his passes for 197 yards, and for
the third straight game did not throw an interception.

	   With his work complete, and Iowa headed for a move up in the BCS
standings after Oklahoma's loss and Notre Dame's unimpressive win,
Banks left the game midway through the third quarter, to a standing
ovation at Kinnick Stadium.

	   "It was almost ridiculous, the way they were cheering,'' said
Banks, who transferred to Iowa from a junior college two years ago.
"But there is still one game to go.''

	   That would be next Saturday at Minnesota. Which now is shaping
up to be one of Iowa's biggest games in years.

	   The Hawkeyes hold a slim lead over Ohio State in the Big Ten
race, but the Buckeyes will clinch the title if they win out, based
on a better overall record. Yet with the top-ranked Sooners losing,
Ohio State suddenly is in line for the Fiesta Bowl.

	   That means Iowa -- whose only loss this season is to Iowa State --
could have the inside track to a trip to its first Rose Bowl since
the 1990 season.

	   Not a bad consolation.

	   "The pursuit of our goals is not over,'' said Maurice Brown,
who caught four passes for 129 yards and two TDs. "We're one game
away. We can't lose focus now.''

	   Northwestern (3-8, 1-6) gave Iowa the chance to take control of
the game early, thanks to a coaching gamble that backfired, and a
communication breakdown on fourth down.

	   The Wildcats tried an onside kick on the opening kickoff, but
Iowa safety Sean Considine picked up the ball and ran to the
Northwestern 25-yard line. Five plays later, Jermelle Lewis scored
on 7-yard run for the Hawkeyes.

	   On Northwestern's next possession, the Wildcats tried to convert
on a fourth-and-1 from their own 40. But Fred Barr spoiled the plan
when he tackled Jason Wright in the flat for no gain, again giving
the Hawkeyes excellent field position.

	   Banks made the Wildcats pay on the very next play when he threw
a 40-yard TD to Maurice Brown. That made the score 14-0 less than
five minutes in.

	   Coach Randy Walker blamed the decision to forgo the punt on a
failure to communicate with players on the field.

	   "We thought they were a good enough team that we had to take
some chances,'' Walker said. "The fourth down early was really one
we didn't want to do. It was a misunderstanding of communication,
and that's my fault.''

	   Northwestern's troubles were deeper than communication. The
Wildcats were held to 100 yards rushing by an Iowa defense that
came into the game as the nation's best at stopping the run.
Wildcats quarterbacks threw for just 199 yards and three
interceptions.

	   For Iowa, it was offense made easy. Fred Russell ran for 100
yards in 17 carries to become the third Hawkeye running back in the
last three years to top 1,000 yards. Iowa rushed for 263 yards and
had 475 total.

	   Iowa coach Kirk Ferentz credited his veteran offensive line for
much of the team's success this season. The line, anchored by four
seniors, including center Bruce Nelson, who made his 46th
consecutive start Saturday, has consistently opened huge holes for
running backs and given Banks time to find receivers.

	   Ferentz rewarded the unit Saturday, bringing them off the field
together after Banks' exit.

	   "The guys that have set the tempo for us are the offensive
linemen,'' Ferentz said. "I'm just so pleased and proud of all
those guys.''

	   Iowa padded its lead when Banks scored on a 9-yard run early in
the second quarter. On Iowa's next possession, Banks hit Brown with
a 65-yard pass that made it 28-7. Banks capped the first-half burst
with a 19-yard keeper for a score.

	   The Hawkeyes continued pouring it on in second half when Ed
Hinkel returned the Wildcats' first punt of the half 58 yards for a
touchdown, making it 42-10.

	   Banks then capped a five-play, 72-yard scoring drive by tossing
a short crossing pass to tight end Dallas Clark, who broke several
tackles and ran for the score that pushed the lead to 49-10.
